The paper deals with distributed algorithms, specifically in the LOCAL model of computation. This suggests that it could belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. The problem being studied is related to graph coloring, which falls under the Discrete Mathematics (cs.DM) sub-category. Additionally, the paper mentions that the problem is complete in the class of all locally checkable graph problems, which suggests that it could also belong to the Computational Complexity (cs.CC) sub-category. The paper also mentions reductions that imply efficient algorithms for many graph problems, which suggests that it could belong to the Graph Theory (cs.GT) sub-category. Finally, the paper mentions the use of polylogarithmic communication rounds, which suggests that it could also belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category.
